The sexual assault endured by women in either wartime or peacetime is not sexual. To the contrary, it is relational hell, much more akin to an abominable conspiracy, complete with all the manipulations of exclusion, control, punishment, betrayal, and lies that go into it, along with the masking of the true motive, which is always power.

While both wars promoted gender inequality by employing armies where most combat roles are controlled by men, and mostly where, percentages suggest, men are more prone to suffer injuries compared to women, the hidden front of the wars - sexual violence against women - is the area where West and East concur.

The fight against sexual violence against women in Liberia was very complex but it was possible to win the remarkable achievement through joint efforts, says, Nobel Peace laureate Leymah Gbowee during the opening of the 5th conference and :Women's Forum for Peace in a World Without Violence on Wheels" organized by the workshop vam in cooperation with the DFG Research Unit “Gender Justice, Law and Society” (GJLS) of Cologne University in Berlin from May 15 - 17, 2019.
